Efficacy 
analyses were done on randomised patients with evaluable post-baseline MRIs; 
safety analyses used the safety-evaluable population.

Headache 
was the only TEAE with incidence ≥ 5% (brexpiprazole, 50 [7.6%] participants; 
placebo, 36 [9.3%] participants).

A birth weight increase of 1 kg was associated with a 44% greater risk 
of food allergy in children (odds ratio [OR], 1.44; 95% CI, 1.04-1.99; 
P = .001), a 17% greater risk of ever allergic dermatitis in children (OR, 1.17; 
95% CI, 1.04-1.32; P = .008), and a 34% greater risk of ever or current allergic 
dermatitis in infants up to 2 years of age (OR, 1.34; 95% CI, 1.08-1.68; 
P = .009).
